# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: periodization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The **10th millennium BC** spanned the years 10,000 BC to 9001 BC (c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] It marks the beginning of the transition from the Palaeolithic to the Neolithic via the interim Mesolithic (Northern Europe and Western Europe) and Epipaleolithic (Levant and Near East) periods, which together form the first part of the Holocene epoch that is generally believed to have begun c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 11.7 ka) and is the current geological epoch.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] It is impossible to precisely date events that happened around the time of this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological analysis, anthropological analysis, and radiometric dating.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The main characteristic of the Holocene has been the worldwide abundance of *Homo sapiens sapiens* (humankind).
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The epoch began in the wake of the Würm glaciation, generally known as the Last Ice Age, which began 109 ka and ended 14 ka, when *Homo sapiens sapiens* was in the Palaeolithic (Old Stone) Age.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Following the Late Glacial Interstadial from 14 ka to 12.9 ka, during which global temperatures rose significantly, the Younger Dryas began.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] This was a temporary reversal of climatic warming to glacial conditions in the Northern Hemisphere and coincided with the end of the Upper Palaeolithic.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 9700 BC, marking the cutover from Pleistocene to Holocene.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In the geologic time scale, there are three (tentatively four) stratigraphic stages of the Holocene beginning c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The starting point for the Greenlandian is the Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point (GSSP) sample from the North Greenland Ice Core Project, which has been correlated with the Younger Dryas.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Greenlandian was succeeded by the "Northgrippian" (to c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] All three stages were officially ratified by the International Commission on Stratigraphy in July 2018.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] It has been proposed that the Meghalayan should be terminated c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 1950 and succeeded by a new stage provisionally called "Anthropocene".
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In the Holocene's first millennium, the Palaeolithic began to be superseded by the Neolithic (New Stone) Age which lasted about 6,000 years, depending on location.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The gradual transition period is sometimes termed Mesolithic (northern and western Europe) or Epipalaeolithic (Levant and Near East).
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The glaciers retreated as the world climate became warmer and that inspired an agricultural revolution, though at first, the dog was probably the only domesticated animal.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] This was accompanied by a social revolution in that humans gained from agriculture the impetus to settle.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Settlement is the key precursor to civilisation, which cannot be achieved by a nomadic lifestyle.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 10,000 BC, is believed to have been more or less stable.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] It has been estimated that there were some five million people at the time of the Last Glacial Maximum, growing to forty million by 5000 BC and 100 million by 1600 BC, which is an average growth rate of 0.027% p.a. from the Neolithic to the Middle Bronze Age.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Around 10,000 BC, most people lived in hunter-gatherer communities scattered across all continents except Antarctica and Zealandia.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] As the Würm/Wisconsin ended, settlement of northern regions was again possible.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Agriculture developed in different parts of the world at different times.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In many places, people learned how to cultivate without outside help; elsewhere, as in western Europe, the skills were imported.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] A decrease in human height accompanied the rise of agriculture near the start of the Holocene period (10,000 BC) and was later correlated with urban population density.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Natufian culture prevailed in the Levant through the 10th millennium and was unusual in that it supported a sedentary or semi-sedentary population even before the introduction of agriculture.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] An early example is 'Ain Mallaha, which may have been the first village in which people were wholly sedentary.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Natufian people are believed to have founded another early settlement on the site of Jericho (Tell es-Sultan) where there is evidence of building between 9600 BC and 8200 BC.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Dates for the Natufian are indeterminate and range broadly from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] It is possible that the early cultivation of figs began in the Jordan River valley sometime after the middle of the 10th millennium.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Besides the fig trees, the people may have begun cultivation of wild plants such as barley and pistachio; and they possibly began herding goats, pigs and cattle.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Agriculture began to be developed by the various communities of the Fertile Crescent, which included the Levant, but it would not be widely practised for another 2,000 years by which time Neolithic culture was becoming well established in many parts of the Near East.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Among the earliest cultivated plants were forms of millet and rice grown in the Middle East, possibly in this millennium but more likely after 9000 BC.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] By about 9500 BC, people in south-eastern Anatolia were harvesting wild grasses and grains.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The earliest evidence of sheep herding has been found in northern Iraq, dated before 9000 BC.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Prehistoric chronology is almost entirely reliant upon the dating of material objects of which pottery is by far the most widespread and the most resistant to decay.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] All locations and generations developed their own shapes, sizes and styles of pottery, including methods and styles of decoration, but there was consistency among stratified deposits and even shards can be classified by time and place.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Pottery is believed to have been discovered independently in various places, beginning with China c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 18,000 BC, and was probably created accidentally by fires lit on clay soil.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The main discovery of pottery dated to the 10th millennium has been at Bosumpra Cave (early tenth-millennium cal.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] BC) on the Kwahu Plateau in southeastern Ghana and Ounjougou (c.9400 BC) in Central Mali, providing evidence of an independent invention of pottery in Sub-Saharan Africa in different climatic zones.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The first chronological pottery system was the Early, Middle and Late Minoan framework devised in the early 20th century by Sir Arthur Evans for his findings at Knossos.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] This covered the Bronze Age in twelve phases from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 1050 BC and the principle was later extended to mainland Greece (Helladic) and the Aegean islands (Cycladic).
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Dame Kathleen Kenyon was the principal archaeologist at Tell es-Sultan (ancient Jericho) and she discovered that there was no pottery there.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The potter's wheel had not yet been invented and, where pottery as such was made, it was still hand-built, often by means of coiling, and pit fired.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Kenyon discovered vessels such as bowls, cups, and plates at Jericho which were made from stone.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] She reasonably surmised that others made from wood or vegetable fibres would have long since decayed.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Using Evans' system as a benchmark, Kenyon divided the Near East Neolithic into phases called Pre-Pottery Neolithic A (PPNA), from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 8800 BC; Pre-Pottery Neolithic B (PPNB), from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 6500 BC; and then Pottery Neolithic (PN), which had varied start-points from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 6500 BC until the beginnings of the Bronze Age towards the end of the 4th millennium.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In the 10th millennium, the Natufian culture co-existed with the PPNA which prevailed in the Levantine and upper Mesopotamian areas of the Fertile Crescent.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In North Africa, Saharan rock art engravings in what is known as the Bubalus (Large Wild Fauna) period have been dated to between 10,000 BC and 7000 BC.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Wall paintings found in Ethiopia and Eritrea depict human activity; some of the older paintings are thought to date back to around 10,000 BC.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In Prehistoric Egypt, a culture of hunter-gatherers replaced a grain grinding culture in 10,000 BC.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Abu Madi tel mounds in the Sinai Peninsula have been dated c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Clovis culture was widely distributed throughout North America.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The people were hunter-gatherers and the culture's duration is believed to have been from c.9050 BC to c.8800 BC.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] There is evidence of increasing use of Clovis point tool technology for hunting.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Elsewhere in North America, the Petroglyphs at Winnemucca Lake, in what is today northwest Nevada, were carved by this time, possibly as early as 12.8 ka or as late as 10 ka.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The sites at Göbekli Tepe, which is home to megalithic structures, Hallan Çemi Tepesi, both in south-eastern Anatolia, and at Tell Qaramel, in north-west Syria, may have been occupied during this millennium.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] It was found out that gastronomy first emerged in Göbekli Tepe in this millennium.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] This most important discovery shedding light on the beginning of gastronomy in Anatolia consists of religious places in which feasts were held in this millennium that were found in the archaeological excavations conducted in Göbekli Tepe in Urfa province which is called the zero point of time.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Sassi di Matera in southern Italy is believed to have been the site of human settlement since the Paleolithic period in this millennium, making it one of the oldest continuously inhabited settlements in history.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] At the Hasankeyf Mound in Turkey, Europe, almost all archaeological data date to this millennium.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In Great Britain, which was not then an island, the Star Carr site in North Yorkshire is believed to have been inhabited by Maglemosian peoples for about 800 years from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Bhimbetka rock shelters, which feature prehistoric cave paintings, earliest being dated to 10,000 BCE, corresponds to the Indian Mesolithic.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] These sites would have been home to a nomadic/hunting society existing in this region.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] In the southern hemisphere, rising sea levels had gradually formed Bass Strait, separating Tasmania from mainland Australia.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] This process is believed to have been complete by about the beginning of the 10th millennium.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Bass Strait had been a plain populated by indigenous people who are thought to have first arrived around 40,000 years ago.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Wisconsin glaciation had sheeted much of North America and, as it retreated, its meltwaters created an immense proglacial lake now known as Lake Agassiz.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Sometime after 10,000 BC, the retreating glaciers created the rock formation on Cannon Mountain in present-day New Hampshire that was known as the Old Man of the Mountain until its collapse in 2003.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The ongoing Quaternary System/Period represents the last 2.58 million years since the end of the Neogene and is officially divided into the Pleistocene and Holocene Series/Epochs.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Holocene has been assigned an age of 11,700 calendar years before 2000 CE which means it began c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] It is preceded in the geological time scale by the Late Pleistocene sub-epoch, also known as the Tarantian Stage/Age, which awaits formal ratification by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) and tentatively spans the time from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] Preceding the Late Pleistocene is the Middle Pleistocene sub-epoch, or Chibanian Stage/Age, which also awaits ratification and tentatively spans the time from c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] 773,000 is sub-divided into two Stages/Ages which have been officially defined: the Gelasian (until c.
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Holocene calendar, devised by Cesare Emiliani in 1993, places its epoch at 10,000 BC (with the year 2026 being rendered as 12026 HE).
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] The Human Era calendar attempts to simplify the calculation of time spans across the BC-CE divide by designating a more universally relevant epoch date: the start of human settlements (instead of the birth of Jesus Christ).
[src:periodization/10-000-bce] CE dates can be converted by adding 10,000 years; converting BC dates requires subtraction from 10,001 (since the Gregorian calendar lacks a year zero).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The **12-hour clock** is a time convention in which the 24 hours of the day are divided into two periods: **a.m.** (from Latin ***ante meridiem***, translating to "before midday") and **p.m.** (from Latin ***post meridiem***, translating to "after midday").
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock has been developed since the second millennium BC and reached its modern form in the 16th century.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour time convention is common in several English-speaking nations and former British colonies, as well as a few other countries.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In English-speaking countries: "12 p.m." usually indicates noon, while "12 a.m." means midnight, but the reverse convention has also been used (see § Confusion at noon and midnight).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The natural day-and-night division of a calendar day forms the fundamental basis as to why each day is split into two cycles.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Originally there were two cycles: one cycle which could be tracked by the position of the Sun (day), followed by one cycle which could be tracked by the Moon and stars (night).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] This eventually evolved into the two 12-hour periods which are used today, one called "a.m." starting at midnight and another called "p.m." starting at noon.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock can be traced back as far as Mesopotamia and ancient Egypt.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Both an Egyptian sundial for daytime use and an Egyptian water clock for night-time use were found in the tomb of Pharaoh Amenhotep I.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] 1500 BC, these clocks divided their respective times of use into 12 hours each.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The ancient Romans also used a 12-hour clock: daylight and nighttime were each divided into 12 equal intervals (of varying duration according to the season).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The nighttime hours were grouped into four *watches* (*vigiliae*).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The first mechanical clocks in the 14th century, if they had dials at all, showed all 24 hours using the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by astronomers' familiarity with the astrolabe and sundial and by their desire to model the Earth's apparent motion around the Sun.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In Northern Europe these dials generally used the 12-hour numbering scheme in Roman numerals but showed both *a.m.* and *p.m.* periods in sequence.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] This is known as the double-XII system and can be seen on many surviving clock faces, such as those at Wells and Exeter.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Elsewhere in Europe, numbering was more likely to be based on the 24-hour system (I to XXIV).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock was used throughout the British Empire.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] During the 15th and 16th centuries, the 12-hour analog dial and time system gradually became established as standard throughout Northern Europe for general public use.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The 24-hour analog dial was reserved for more specialized applications, such as astronomical clocks and chronometers.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Most analog clocks and watches today use the 12-hour dial, on which the shorter hour hand rotates once every 12 hours and twice in one day.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Some analog clock dials have an inner ring of numbers along with the standard 1-to-12 numbered ring.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The number 12 is paired either with a 00 or a 24, while the numbers 1 through 11 are paired with the numbers 13 through 23, respectively.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] This modification allows the clock to also be read in 24-hour notation.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] This kind of 12-hour clock can be found in countries where the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Even in those countries where the 12-hour clock is predominant, there are frequently contexts (such as science, medicine, the military or transport) in which the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In most countries, however, the 24-hour clock is the standard system used, especially in writing.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Some nations in Europe and Latin America use a combination of the two, preferring the 12-hour system in colloquial speech but using the 24-hour system in written form and in formal contexts.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock in speech often uses phrases such as*... in the morning*,*... in the afternoon*,*... in the evening*, and *... at night*.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] *Rider's British Merlin* almanac for 1795 and a similar almanac for 1773 published in London used them.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Other than in English-speaking countries and some Spanish-speaking countries, the terms *a.m.* and *p.m.* are seldom used and often unknown.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In most countries, computers by default show the time in 24-hour notation.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Most operating systems, including Microsoft Windows and Unix-like systems such as Linux and macOS, activate the 12-hour notation by default for a limited number of language and region settings.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] This behaviour can be changed by the user, such as with the Windows operating system's "Region and Language" settings.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The Latin abbreviations *a.m.* and *p.m.* (often written "am" and "pm", "AM" and "PM", or "A.M." and "P.M.") are used in English (and Spanish).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] When abbreviations and phrases are omitted, one may rely on sentence context and societal norms to reduce ambiguity.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] For example, if one commutes to work at "9:00", 9:00 a.m. may be implied, but if a social dance is scheduled to begin at "9:00", it may begin at 9:00 p.m.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The terms "a.m." and "p.m." are abbreviations of the Latin *ante meridiem* (before midday) and *post meridiem* (after midday).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Depending on the style guide referenced, the abbreviations "a.m." and "p.m." are variously written in small capitals ("am" and "pm"), uppercase letters without a period ("AM" and "PM"), uppercase letters with periods, or lowercase letters ("am" and "pm" or "a.m." and "p.m.").
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Some style guides suggest the use of a space between the number and the a.m. or p.m. abbreviation.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Style guides recommend not using a.m. and p.m. without a time preceding it.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The hour/minute separator varies between countries: some use a colon, others use a period (full stop), and still others use the letter h.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] (In some usages, particularly "military time", of the 24-hour clock, there is no separator between hours and minutes.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In speaking, it is common to round the time to the nearest five minutes and/or express the time as the past (or to) the closest hour; for example, "five past five" (5:05).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Minutes *past* the hour means those minutes are added to the hour; "ten past five" means 5:10.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Minutes *to, till* and *of* the hour mean those minutes are subtracted; "ten of five", "ten till five", and "ten to five" all mean 4:50.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Fifteen minutes is often called a *quarter hour*, and thirty minutes is often known as a *half hour*.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] For example, 5:15 can be phrased "(a) quarter past five" or "five-fifteen"; 5:30 can be "half past five", "five-thirty" or simply "half five".
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] The time 8:45 may be spoken as "eight forty-five" or "(a) quarter to nine".
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Polish, rounding off is mandatory when using (spoken) 12-hour clock, but disallowed when using 24 hour notation.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] 15:12 might be pronounced as "quarter past three" or "fifteen-twelve", but *not* "three-twelve" or "quarter past fifteen".
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In older English, it was common for the number 25 to be expressed as "five-and-twenty".
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In this way the time 8:35 might have been phrased as "five-and-twenty to 9", although this styling fell out of fashion in the later part of the 1900s and is now rarely used.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Instead of meaning 5:30, the "half five" expression is sometimes used to mean 4:30, or "halfway to five", especially for regions such as the American Midwest and other areas that have been particularly influenced by German culture.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] This meaning follows the pattern choices of many Germanic and Slavic languages, including Serbo-Croatian, Dutch, Danish, Russian, Norwegian, and Swedish, as well as Hungarian, Finnish, and the languages of the Baltic States.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Moreover, in situations where the relevant hour is obvious or has been recently mentioned, a speaker might omit the hour and just say "quarter to (the hour)", "half past" or "ten till" to avoid an elaborate sentence in informal conversations.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] These forms are often commonly used in television and radio broadcasts that cover multiple time zones at one-hour intervals.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Minutes may be expressed as an exact number of minutes past the hour specifying the time of day (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is "six thirty-two").
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Additionally, when expressing the time using the "past (after)" or "to (before)" formula, it is conventional to choose the number of minutes below 30 (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is conventionally "twenty-eight minutes to seven" rather than "thirty-two minutes past six").
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In spoken English, full hours are often represented by the numbered hour followed by *o'clock* (10:00 as *ten o'clock*, 2:00 as *two o'clock*).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] This may be followed by the "a.m." or "p.m." designator, though some phrases such as *in the morning, in the afternoon, in the evening,* or *at night* more commonly follow analog-style terms such as *o'clock, half past three,* and *quarter to four.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] O'clock* itself may be omitted, telling a time as *four a.m.* or *four p.m.* Minutes ":01" to ":09" are usually pronounced as *oh one* to *oh nine* (*nought* or *zero* can also be used instead of *oh*).
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Minutes ":10" to ":59" are pronounced as their usual number-words.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] For instance, 6:02 a.m. can be pronounced *six oh two a.m.* whereas 6:32 a.m. could be told as *six thirty-two a.m.*.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] It is not always clear what times "12:00 a.m." and "12:00 p.m." denote.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] In Latin, **ante meridiem** (a.m.) means "before midday" and **post meridiem** (p.m.) means "after midday".
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Since noon is neither before nor after itself, the terms a.m. and p.m. do not apply.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Although noon could be denoted "12 m.", this is seldom done and also does not resolve the question of how to indicate midnight.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] By convention, "12 a.m." denotes midnight and "12 p.m." denotes noon.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] However, many style guides recommend against using either because of the potential for confusion.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Many recommend instead using the unambiguous terms "12 noon" and "12 midnight", or simply "noon" and "midnight".
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] These include *The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language*, *The Canadian Press Stylebook*, and the NIST's "Frequently asked questions (FAQ)" web page.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Alternatively, some recommend referring to one minute before or after 12:00, especially when referring to midnight (for example, "11:59 p.m." or "12:01 a.m.").
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] These include the UK's National Physical Laboratory "FAQ-Time" web page.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] That has become common in the United States in legal contracts and for airplane, bus, or train schedules, though some schedules use other conventions.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Occasionally, when trains run at regular intervals, the pattern may be broken at midnight by displacing the midnight departure one or more minutes, such as to 11:59 p.m. or 12:01 a.m.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Some authors have been known to use the reverse of the normal convention.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Richards in his book *Mapping Time* (1999) provided a diagram in which 12 a.m. means noon and 12 p.m. means midnight.
[src:periodization/12-hour-clock] Historically, the style manual of the United States Government Printing Office used 12 a.m. for noon and 12 p.m. for midnight, though this was reversed in its 2008 editions.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:periodization/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Clocks and watches with a **24-hour analog dial** have an hour hand that makes one complete revolution—360°—in a full day, or 24 hours per revolution.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In contrast, the more familiar 12-hour analog dial has an hour hand that completes two revolutions per day, or 12 hours per revolution.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Twenty-four-hour analog clocks and watches are commonly used by logistics workers, firefighters, police officers, paramedics, nurses, pilots, scientists, and military personnel.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] They are often preferred because they present an unambiguous representation of the entire day at once.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] This definition specifically refers to the use of a full circular dial to represent a 24-hour cycle.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Simply using numbers from 0 to 23 (or 1 to 24) is known as the *24-hour clock system*.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials also use 24-hour analog dials, as the shadow follows a path that repeats approximately once per day.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many sundials are marked with the double-XII (or double-12) system, where the numbers I to XII (or 1 to 12) appear twice—once for the morning and once for the afternoon and evening.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Thus, VI (6) appears twice on many sundial dials: once near sunrise and once near sunset.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Modern 24-hour analog dials—aside from sundials—are almost always marked with 24 numbers or hour markers around the edge, following the 24-hour clock system.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Because they display the entire day in one rotation, they do not require AM or PM indicators.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] The ancient Egyptians divided the day into 24 hours.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] There are diagrams of circles divided into 24 sections in the astronomical ceiling in the tomb of Senemut.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials use some or all of the 24-hour dial, because they show the position of the sun in the sky.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sometimes, for aesthetic rather than practical reasons, all the 24 hour marks are shown.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Medieval clocks often used the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by the widespread example of the astrolabe.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Northern Europe, the double-XII system was preferred: two sets of the Roman numerals I to XII were used, one on the left side for the night and morning hours, and another set on the right side of the dial to represent the afternoon and evening hours.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Italy, the numbers from 1 to 24 (I to XXIV in Roman numerals) were used, leading to the widespread use of the 24-hour system in that country.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] On Italian clocks, though, the I was often shown at the right side of the dial, rather than the top.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] This probably reflects the influence of the Italian timekeeping system, which started counting the hours of the day at sunset or twilight.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In northern Europe, the double-XII system was gradually superseded during the 14th and 15th centuries by the single-XII (12-hour system), leading to the widespread adoption of the 12-hour dial for popular use.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 24-hour analog dial continued to be used, but primarily by technicians, astronomers, scientists, and clockmakers.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] John Harrison, Thomas Tompion, and Mudge built a number of clocks with 24-hour analog dials, particularly when building astronomical and nautical instruments.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour dials were also used on sidereal clocks.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] The famous Big Ben clock in London has a 24-hour dial as part of the mechanism, although it is not visible from the outside.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Astronauts used the 24-hour format due to the lack of day/night in the space environment.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 20th century, the 24-hour analog dial was adopted by radio amateurs, media, pilots, maritime, submariners, government, diplomats and for military use.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour analog watches and clocks are still being manufactured today, and are sought after by collectors and enthusiasts.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Manufacturers who make 24-hour analog watches include Glycine, Raketa, Vostok, Fortis, Poljot, Swatch, and many others.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] A few rare variants place noon and midnight at the right and left sides.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] There is no ambiguity if the 24-hour numbering is used.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the United States, the government and military commonly use 24-hour clocks having noon at the bottom; the variant with noon at the top is far less common.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Multiple time zones can be displayed by having multiple hour hands or a rotating bezel.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel is a ring around the outside of the watch's face.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] When it is used, the top of the watch always represents midnight (or noon) GMT.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel, which also has hour markings, is then rotated so that its numbering represents local time.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] So, a pilot always has GMT time available for talking to air traffic control and, when they land, only has to rotate the bezel to "set" the watch to their new local time.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Glycine was the first to feature a 24-hour rotating bezel in 1953 with the Airman No.1 pilot watch.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] The design became widely known when Rolex designed the Rolex GMT Master for Pan-Am pilots in 1954.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] A 24-hour watch with a compass card dial can be used to determine direction when set to local noon and used in conjunction with the Sun.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many (but not all) digital watches can be set to show the time in 24-hour format.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] A common use for the 24-hour analog method of representing time is for showing the way the time of day depends on one's location.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] George Orwell uses the 12-hour and 24-hour dials to symbolize the old and new worlds in his novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 12-hour dial is a relic of pre-revolutionary society, used to represent the desirable past; the 24-hour dial and time system is the compulsory standard imposed by the Party, and represents both conformity and the undesirable nature of the new world.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] It was a bright cold day in April, and the clocks were striking thirteen.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 1927 film *Metropolis*, the opening scene shows both a 24-hour analog clock and a 10-hour (decimal) analog clock, one above the other.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] Both are used to convey the impression of an alien and highly efficient society.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Jules Verne's 1870 science fiction masterpiece *Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas*, Captain Nemo remarks that the clocks in the *Nautilus* use a 24-hour dial: "Now, look at that clock: it's electric, it runs with an accuracy rivaling the finest chronometers.
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] I've had it divided into twenty–four hours like Italian clocks, since neither day nor night, sun nor moon, exist for me, but only this artificial light that I import into the depths of the seas!
[src:periodization/24-hour-analogue-dial] A watch with a 24-hour analog dial is important to the resolution of Alfred Bester's 1953 short story "The Roller Coaster".
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The modern **24-hour clock** is the convention of timekeeping in which the day runs from midnight to midnight and is divided into 24 hours.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] This is indicated by the hours (and minutes) passed since midnight, from 00(:00) to 23(:59), with 24(:00) as an option to indicate the end of the day.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] This system, as opposed to the 12-hour clock, is the most commonly used time notation in the world today, and is used by the international standard ISO 8601.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] A number of countries, particularly English speaking, use the 12-hour clock, or a mixture of the 24- and 12-hour time systems.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In countries where the 12-hour clock is dominant, some professions prefer to use the 24-hour clock.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] For example, in the practice of medicine, the 24-hour clock is generally used in documentation of care as it prevents any ambiguity as to when events occurred in a patient's medical history.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] To indicate the exact end of the day, hh may take the value 24, with mm and ss taking the value 00.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In the case of a leap second, the value of ss may extend to 60.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] A leading zero is added for numbers under 10, but it is optional for the hours.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The leading zero is very commonly used in computer applications, and always used when a specification requires it (for example, ISO 8601).
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Where subsecond resolution is required, the seconds can be a decimal fraction; that is, the fractional part follows a decimal dot or comma, as in 01:23:45.678.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The most commonly used separator symbol between hours, minutes and seconds is the colon, which is also the symbol used in ISO 8601.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In the past, some European countries used the dot on the line as a separator, but most national standards on time notation have since then been changed to the international standard colon.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In some contexts (including some computer protocols and military time), no separator is used and times are written as, for example, "2359".
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In the 24-hour time notation, the day begins at midnight, 00:00 or 0:00, and the last minute of the day begins at 23:59.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In the ISO 8601 notation, 24:00 may also be used to refer to midnight at the end of a given date — that is, 24:00 of one day is the same time as 00:00 of the following day.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The notation 24:00 mainly serves to refer to the exact end of a day in a time interval.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] A typical usage is giving opening hours ending at midnight (e.g.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Similarly, some bus and train timetables show 00:00 as departure time and 24:00 as arrival time.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Legal contracts often run from the start date at 00:00 until the end date at 24:00.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] While the 24-hour notation unambiguously distinguishes between midnight at the start (00:00) and end (24:00) of any given date, there is no commonly accepted distinction among users of the 12-hour notation.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Style guides and military communication regulations in some English-speaking countries discourage the use of 24:00 even in the 24-hour notation, and recommend reporting times near midnight as 23:59 or 00:01 instead.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Sometimes the use of 00:00 is also avoided.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In variance with this, an older version of the correspondence manual for the United States Navy and United States Marine Corps specified 0001 to 2400.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The manual was updated in June 2015 to use 0000 to 2359.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Time-of-day notations beyond 24:00 (such as 24:01 or 25:00 instead of 00:01 or 01:00) are not commonly used and not covered by the relevant standards.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] However, they have been used occasionally in some special contexts in the United Kingdom, France, Spain, Canada, Japan, South Korea, Hong Kong, and China where business hours extend beyond midnight, such as broadcast television production and scheduling.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The GTFS public transport schedule listings file format has the concept of service days and expects times beyond 24:00 for trips that run after midnight.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] For example, Microsoft Windows and macOS activate the 12-hour notation by default only if a computer is in a handful of specific language and region settings.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The 24-hour system is commonly used in text-based interfaces.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] POSIX programs such as `ls` default to displaying timestamps in 24-hour format.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In the United States (a country which uses 12-hour clocks), the 24-hour clock is often referred to as *military time*.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] There is, however, a more specific standard for military time which refines the acceptable written and spoken forms of times on the 24-hour clock.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The first mechanical public clocks introduced in Italy were mechanical 24-hour clocks which counted the 24 hours of the day from one-half hour after sunset to the evening of the following day.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The 24th hour was the last hour of day time.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The modern 24-hour system is a late-19th century adaptation of the German midnight-starting system, and then prevailed in the world with the exception of some Anglophone countries.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Striking clocks had to produce 300 strokes each day, which required a lot of rope, and wore out the mechanism quickly, so some localities switched to ringing sequences of 1 to 12 twice, or 1 to 6 repeated four times.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Sandford Fleming, the engineer-in-chief of the Canadian Intercolonial Railway, was an early proponent of using the 24-hour clock as part of a programme to reform timekeeping, which also included establishing time zones and a standard prime meridian.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The Canadian Pacific Railway was among the first organisations to adopt the 24-hour clock, at midsummer 1886.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] A report by a government committee in the United Kingdom noted Italy as the first country among those mentioned to adopt 24-hour time nationally, in 1893.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Other European countries followed: France adopted it in 1912 (the French army in 1909), followed by Denmark (1916), and Greece (1917).
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] By 1920, Spain, Portugal, Belgium, and Switzerland had switched, followed by Turkey (1925), and Germany (1927).
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] By the early 1920s, many countries in Latin America had also adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] Some of the railways in India had switched before the outbreak of the war.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] During World War I, the British Royal Navy adopted the 24-hour clock in 1915, and the Allied armed forces followed soon after, with the British Army switching officially in 1918.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The Canadian armed forces first started to use the 24-hour clock in late 1917.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In 1920, the United States Navy was the first United States organisation to adopt the system; the United States Army, however, did not officially adopt the 24-hour clock until 1 July 1942.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The use of the 24-hour clock in the United Kingdom has grown steadily since the beginning of the 20th century, although attempts to make the system official failed more than once.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In 1934, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) switched to the 24-hour clock for broadcast announcements and programme listings.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] The experiment was halted after five months following a lack of enthusiasm from the public, and the BBC continued using the 12-hour clock.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In the same year, Pan American World Airways Corporation and Western Airlines in the United States both adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] In modern times, the BBC uses a mixture of both the 12-hour and the 24-hour clock.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] British Rail, London Transport, and the London Underground switched to the 24-hour clock for timetables in 1964.
[src:periodization/24-hour-clock] A mixture of the 12- and 24-hour clocks similarly prevails in other English-speaking Commonwealth countries: French speakers have adopted the 24-hour clock in Canada much more broadly than English speakers, and Australia as well as New Zealand also use both systems.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] In metaphysics, the **A series** and the **B series** are two different descriptions of the temporal ordering relation among events.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] The two series differ principally in their use of tense to describe the temporal relation between events and the resulting ontological implications regarding time.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] John McTaggart introduced these terms in 1908, in an argument for the unreality of time.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] They are now commonly used by contemporary philosophers of time.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Metaphysical debate about temporal orderings reaches back to the ancient Greek philosophers Heraclitus and Parmenides.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Parmenides thought that reality is timeless and unchanging.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Heraclitus, in contrast, believed that the world is a process of ceaseless change, flux and decay.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Reality for Heraclitus is dynamic and ephemeral, in a state of constant flux, as in his famous statement that it is impossible to step twice into the same river (since the river is flowing).
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] McTaggart distinguished the ancient conceptions as a set of relations.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] According to McTaggart, there are two distinct modes in which all events can be ordered in time.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] In the first mode (the A series of temporal positions), events are ordered as future, present, and past.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Futurity and pastness allow for degrees, while the present does not.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] When we speak of time in this way, we are speaking in terms of a series of positions which run from the remote past through the recent past to the present, and from the present through the near future all the way to the remote future.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] The essential characteristic of this descriptive modality is **McTaggartian change**: the continual transformation of an event's position within the series of temporal positions, whereby the event is first future, then present, and then past.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] In this sense, change is understood as temporal passage itself, through which events acquire and lose the determinations of futurity, presentness, and pastness.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Moreover, assertions made according to this modality correspond to the temporal perspective of the person who utters them.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] This is the A series of temporal positions.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Although originally McTaggart defined tenses as relational qualities, i.e., qualities that events possess by standing in a certain relation to something outside of time (that does not change its position in time), today it is popularly believed that he treated tenses as monadic properties.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Later philosophers have independently inferred that McTaggart must have understood tense as monadic because English tenses are normally expressed by the non-relational singular predicates "is past", "is present" and "is future", as noted by R.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] An important difference between the two series is that while events continuously change their position in the A series, their position in the B series does not.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] If an event is ever earlier than some events and later than the rest, it is always earlier than and later than those very events.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Furthermore, while events acquire their A-series determinations through a relation to something outside of time, their B-series determinations hold between the events that constitute the B series.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] This is the B series, and the philosophy that says all truths about time can be reduced to B series statements is the B-theory of time.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] The logic and the linguistic expression of the two series are radically different.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] The A series is *tensed* and the B series is *tenseless*.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] For example, the assertion "it is raining here today" is a tensed assertion because it depends on the temporal perspective—the present—of the person who utters it, while the assertion "It rained here on 30 June 2026" is tenseless because it does not so depend.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] From the point of view of their truth-values, the two propositions are identical (both true or both false) if the first assertion is made on 30 June 2026.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] The non-temporal relation of precedence between two events, say "E precedes F", does not change over time (excluding from this discussion the issue of the relativity of temporal order of causally disconnected events in the theory of relativity).
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] On the other hand, the character of being "past, present or future" of the events "E" or "F" does change with time.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] In the image of McTaggart the passage of time consists in the fact that terms ever further in the future pass into the present...or that the present advances toward terms ever farther in the future.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the first point of view, we speak as if the B series slides along a fixed A series.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the second point of view, we speak as if the A series slides along a fixed B series.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] There are two principal varieties of the A-theory, presentism and the growing block universe.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Both assume an objective present, but presentism assumes that only present objects exist, while the growing block universe assumes both present and past objects exist, but not future ones.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Views that assume no objective present and are therefore versions of the B-theory include eternalism and four-dimensionalism.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] Vincent Conitzer argues that A-theory is related to Benj Hellie's vertiginous question and Caspar Hare's ideas of egocentric presentism and perspectival realism.
[src:periodization/a-series-and-b-series] He argues that A-theory being true and "now" being metaphysically distinguished from other moments of time implies that the "I" is also metaphysically distinguished from other first-person perspectives.
[src:periodization/aspro-chronology] The **ASPRO chronology** is a nine-period dating system of the ancient Near East used by the Maison de l'Orient et de la Méditerranée for archaeological sites aged between 14,000 and 5,700 BP.
[src:periodization/aspro-chronology] First published in 1994, ASPRO stands for the "Atlas des sites du Proche-Orient" (Atlas of Near East archaeological sites), a French publication pioneered by Francis Hours and developed by other scholars such as Olivier Aurenche.
[src:periodization/aspro-chronology] In 2001, the institute revised the chronology of the first six periods based on newer carbon data and calibration curves.
[src:periodization/aspro-chronology] In Period 3 an early and late phase could be distinguished, but Periods 4 and 5 were merged.
[src:periodization/aspro-chronology] Overall they found more overlap in time between different cultural phases between different sites.
[src:periodization/periodization] In historiography, **periodization** is the process or study of categorizing the past into discrete, quantified, and named blocks of time for the purpose of study or analysis.
[src:periodization/periodization] This is usually done to understand current and historical processes, and the causality that might have linked those events.
[src:periodization/periodization] Periodizations can provide a convenient segmentation of time, wherein events within the period might consist of relatively similar characteristics.
[src:periodization/periodization] However, determining the precise beginning and ending of any 'period' is often arbitrary, since it has changed over time and over the course of history.
[src:periodization/periodization] Systems of periodization are more or less arbitrary, yet it provides a framework to help us understand them.
[src:periodization/periodization] Periodizing labels are continually challenged and redefined, but once established, period "brands" are so convenient that many are hard to change.
[src:periodization/periodization] The practice of dividing history into ages or periods is as early as the development of writing, and can be traced to the Sumerian period.
[src:periodization/periodization] The *Sumerian King List*, dating to the second millennium BC—which for most parts is not considered historically accurate—is "periodized" into dynastic regnal eras.
[src:periodization/periodization] The classical division into a Golden Age, Silver Age, Bronze Age, Heroic Age, and Iron Age goes back to Hesiod in the 8th–7th century BC.
[src:periodization/periodization] One Biblical periodization scheme commonly used in the Middle Ages was Saint Paul's theological division of history into three ages: the first before the age of Moses (under nature); the second under Mosaic law (under law); the third in the age of Christ (under grace).
[src:periodization/periodization] But perhaps the most widely discussed periodization scheme of the Middle Ages was the Six Ages of the World, written by the early 5th century AD, where every age was a thousand years counting from Adam to the present, with the present time (in the Middle Ages) being the sixth and final age.
[src:periodization/periodization] Periodizing blocks might overlap, conflict or contradict one another.
[src:periodization/periodization] Some have a cultural usage (the "Gilded Age"), others refer to prominent historical events ('the Interwar period), while others are defined by decimal numbering systems ('the 1960s', 'the 17th century').
[src:periodization/periodization] Other periods are named from influential individuals (the 'Napoleonic Era', the 'Victorian Era', and the 'Porfiriato').
[src:periodization/periodization] Some of these usages will also be geographically specific.
[src:periodization/periodization] This is especially true of periodizing labels derived from individuals or ruling dynasties, such as the Jacksonian Era in America, the Meiji Era in Japan, or the Merovingian Period in France.
[src:periodization/periodization] Cultural terms may also have a limited reach.
[src:periodization/periodization] Thus the concept of the "Romantic period" is largely meaningless outside the Western world of Europe and European-influenced cultures.
[src:periodization/periodization] Likewise, 'the 1960s', though technically applicable to anywhere in the world according to Common Era numbering, has a certain set of specific cultural connotations in certain countries.
[src:periodization/periodization] For this reason, it may be possible to say such things as "The 1960s never occurred in Spain".
[src:periodization/periodization] This would mean that the sexual revolution, counterculture, youth rebellion and so on never developed during that decade in Spain's conservative Roman Catholic culture and under Francisco Franco's authoritarian regime.
[src:periodization/periodization] The historian Arthur Marwick mentions that "the 1960s' began in the late 1950s and ended in the early 1970s".
[src:periodization/periodization] This was because the cultural and economic conditions that define the meaning of the period covers more than the accidental fact of a 10-year block beginning with the number 6.
[src:periodization/periodization] This extended usage is termed the 'long 1960s'.
[src:periodization/periodization] This usage derives from other historians who have adopted labels such as "the long 19th century" (1789–1914) to reconcile arbitrary decimal chronology with meaningful cultural and social phases.
[src:periodization/periodization] Eric Hobsbawm has also argued for what he calls "the short twentieth century", encompassing the period from the First World War through to the end of the Cold War.
[src:periodization/periodization] Periodizing terms often have negative or positive connotations that may affect their usage.
[src:periodization/periodization] This includes *Victorian*, which often negatively suggests sexual repression and class conflict.
[src:periodization/periodization] Other labels such as *Renaissance* have strongly positive characteristics.
[src:periodization/periodization] As a result, these terms sometimes extend in meaning.
[src:periodization/periodization] Thus the *English Renaissance* is often used for a period largely identical to the *Elizabethan Period* or reign of Elizabeth I, and begins some 200 years later than the Italian Renaissance.
[src:periodization/periodization] However the *Carolingian Renaissance* is said to have occurred during the reign of the Frankish king Charlemagne, and his immediate successors, and the Macedonian Renaissance occurred in the Eastern Roman Empire.
[src:periodization/periodization] Other examples, neither of which constituted a "rebirth" in the sense of revival, are the *American Renaissance* of the 1820s–1860s, referring mainly to literature, and the *Harlem Renaissance* of the 1920s, referring mainly to literature but also to music and the visual arts.
[src:periodization/periodization] The conception of a 'rebirth' of Classical Latin learning is first credited to the Italian poet Petrarch (1304–1374), the father of Renaissance Humanism, but the conception of a rebirth has been in common use since Petrarch's time.
[src:periodization/periodization] The dominant usage of the word *Renaissance* refers to the cultural changes that occurred in Italy that culminated in the High Renaissance around 1500–1530.
[src:periodization/periodization] This concept applies dominantly to the visual arts, and the work of Michelangelo, Raphael, and Leonardo da Vinci.
[src:periodization/periodization] Secondarily it is applied to other arts, but it is questionable whether it is useful to describe a phase in economic, social and political history.
[src:periodization/periodization] Many professional historians now refer to the historical periods commonly known as the Renaissance and the Reformation as the start of the Early Modern Period, which extends much later.
[src:periodization/periodization] There is a gradual change in the courses taught and books published to correspond to the change in period nomenclature, which in part reflects differences between social history and cultural history.
[src:periodization/periodization] The new nomenclature suggests a broader geographical coverage and a growing attention to the relationships between Europe and the wider world.
[src:periodization/periodization] The term Middle Ages also derives from Petrarch.
[src:periodization/periodization] He was comparing his own period to the Ancient or Classical world, seeing his time as a time of rebirth after a dark intermediate period, the Middle Ages.
[src:periodization/periodization] The idea that the Middle Ages was a middle phase between two other large scale periodizing concepts, Ancient and Modern, still persists.
[src:periodization/periodization] It can be subdivided into the Early, High and Late Middle Ages.
[src:periodization/periodization] The term Dark Ages is no longer in common use among modern scholars because of the difficulty of using it neutrally, though some writers have attempted to retain it and divest it of its negative connotations.
[src:periodization/periodization] The term "Middle Ages" and especially the adjective *medieval* can also have a negative ring in colloquial use, but does not carry over into academic terminology.
[src:periodization/periodization] However, other terms, such as Gothic architecture, used to refer to a style typical of the High Middle Ages have largely lost the negative connotations they initially had, acquiring new meanings over time (see Gothic architecture and Goth subculture).
[src:periodization/periodization] The Gothic and the Baroque were both named during subsequent stylistic periods when the preceding style was unpopular.
[src:periodization/periodization] The word "Gothic" was applied as a pejorative term to all things Northern European and, hence, barbarian, probably first by Giorgio Vasari.
[src:periodization/periodization] He coined the term "Gothic" in an effort to describe (particularly architecture) what he found objectionable.
[src:periodization/periodization] The word *baroque*—derived from similar words in Portuguese, Spanish, or French—literally refers to an irregular or misshapen pearl.
[src:periodization/periodization] Its first use outside the field of jewellery manufacture was in the early 18th century, as a criticism of music that was viewed as over-complicated and rough.
[src:periodization/periodization] Later, the term was also used to describe architecture and art.
[src:periodization/periodization] The Baroque period was first designated as such in the 19th century, and is generally considered to have begun around 1600 in all media.
[src:periodization/periodization] Music history places the end of the period in the year 1750 with the death of J.
[src:periodization/periodization] Bach, while art historians consider the main period to have ended significantly earlier in most areas.
[src:periodization/periodization] In archeology, the usual method for periodization of the distant prehistoric past is to rely on changes in material culture and technology, such as the Stone Age, Bronze Age and Iron Age and their sub-divisions also based on different styles of material remains.
[src:periodization/periodization] Despite the development over recent decades of the ability through radiocarbon dating and other scientific methods to give actual dates for many sites or artefacts, these long-established schemes seem likely to remain in use.
[src:periodization/periodization] In many cases neighbouring cultures with writing have left some history of cultures without it, which may be used.
[src:periodization/periodization] The system further underwent subdivisions, including the 1865 partitioning of the Stone Age into Palaeolithic, Mesolithic and Neolithic periods by John Lubbock.
[src:periodization/periodization] Some events or short periods of change have such a drastic effect on the cultures they affect that they form a natural break in history.
[src:periodization/periodization] These are often marked by the widespread use of both *pre-* and *post-* phrases centered on the event, as in *pre-Reformation* and *post-Reformation*, or *pre-colonial* and *post-colonial*.
[src:periodization/periodization] Both pre-war and post-war are still understood to refer to World War II, though at some future point the phrases will need to be altered to make that clear.
[src:periodization/periodization] In French and Romance-language historiography, the early modern period is labelled "modern" (Spanish: *edad moderna*) and the late modern and contemporary periods are grouped as "contemporary" (Spanish: *edad contemporánea*).
[src:periodization/periodization] Although *post-classical* is synonymous with the Middle Ages of Western Europe, the term *post-classical* is not necessarily a member of the traditional tripartite periodization of Western European history into 'classical', 'middle' and 'modern'.
